{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_inxs_ver01/data/sn89051168/00393343308/1910061601/0791.xml":{"full_text":"Ig Ipine JBlukk Daily Grapbic.\nA MEMBER OF THE IIEAEST NEWS SYNDICATE.\nPIKE BLUFF, ARKANSAS, THURSDAY MORNING, JUX\nVOL. XVI.\nE 10. 1 DIO.\nNUMBER ISrf.\nGREAT INTEREST\nIN TJE EXHISr\nFive Hundred Persons At\ntended Lectures and In\njected Exhibit\nHERE LAST NIG-Hl\nPr. Caldwell Among the Speakers\nPnblic Health Hints are Giv\nen Forcibly There*\nI _\nThe public exhibit now in progres\nat No. 408 Main street under the Xat\nional Association for the Study an\nPrevention of Tuberculosis is one o\nthe greatest opportunities ever of\nfered in this city for the benefit o\nthe public and 'business interests o\nthe city. Walter L. Cosper, manage\nof the exhibit, is well pleased with th\nattendance at the evening lecture\nand programmes. Last night ove\nfive hundred interested spectator\nvisited the building.\nIn the way of aiding the public b\nmore forcibly see the destructioi\nwrought by the great white plagu\nand enlightening them how to prevent\nthe exehibit is a gem. Simply a visi\nto the exhibit and a look at the pic\ntures of the disease and the resorti\nto which the sufferer goes is an edu\ncation. Over five hundred picture!\nare hung upon the walls of the build\nIng. Many are taken of lungs of i\nconsumptive and others show th<\ndeaths and places of the deaths, ac\ncording to the population.\nOne of the most interesting sub\njects of the exhibit is the method!\nfor preventing the disease. Mr. Cos\nper takes especial interest in show\niyg to the callers the various ways\njPticfaieh one may sleep to prevent th<\nJjtse. Chairs and cots are shown\nEofminiature house with opened win'\ndow and outer covering are on dis\nplay. Some of the famous methods\nused in the western resorts for suf\nferers from tuberculosis are shown. Ai\nthe farther end of the hal.1 in contrasl\nIs shown two bed rooms. One is\nwell lighted with open window anc\nfresh air. The other is dirty, dark\ndose and stuffy.\nThe program last night was one oi\nthe best of the week. Mayor Toney\npresided.\nDr. J. L. Caldwell, secretary of the\nBoard of Trade, who is taking a great\nInterest in the exhibit, was the firs!\nspeaker. Dr. Caldwell made one ol\nthe most forceful and logical talks on\nthis much discussed subject evei\nheard in the city. Tuberculosis\nProm a Business Standpoint.\u201d was\nOr. Caldwell\u2019s subject. In his dis\ncourses he stated that when the death\nrecord of the nation showed as many\n7 Know\n-'Our\nQuality\nle Progress\nas 200,000 from tuberculosis, that tin\ndisease should certainly be taken a.\na destroyer of business. Dr. Caldwel\nI\" also told that during four years of tin\ncivil war the two armies lost men\nfrom wounds and bullets to the num\nher of 270,000 each, and during tin\nsame period recently, the death rat.\nshowed 640,000 deaths to be due fron\ntuberculosis. The authorities in Lit\nI tie Rock also state that out of an en\ni tu'e deatil rate of thirty-five negroes\nidunng the Past year, twenty-two hat\nbeen caused by tuberculosis.\nDr. W. S. Stewart spoke on \u201cEcono\nimics \u00b0f Tuberculosis.\u2019\u2019 Dr. stew\nI art\u2019s discourse was highly interesting\nand practical. The fading of onc\u00ab\nstrong empires and nations, Dr. Stew\n\u25a0art stat<?d, was due to disease, which\nI brought on moral and political degen\neracy. Among other things he said\nIf we as a people and a nation main\n3 tain our supremacy and prestige wt\nmust above all, conserve the racial\nj stock by making every effort to stamp\nf out disease. Normal, healthy men\ncare for and provide for their des\nf cen(Iants. A normal, healthy race ol\nH men> and such alone, will enact the\nr laws\u2019 or develop the public sentiment\nneede(1 to conserve natural resources\nfor( generations yet unborn.\np \u201cTuberculosis still remains the\nj cbfef source of death and from an eco\nI nomic point of view, as well as oth\ners> is a subject of prime importance.\nTuberculosis is responsible for about\n^-seventh of all our deaths and\nmore man one-third of all who die\nbetwefc- the ages of fifteen and thirty\n_ ifive succumb from this disease. There\ni are more than half a million consump\ntives in the United States today, and\neach year this great white plague ear\nrfes away 150,000 of our people.\u201d Dr.\ni Stewart brought out many other\nPoints during his talk, until his sub\nject had been completely handled from\nhis point of view.\nI Dr. W. S. Crutcher followed witu a\n.brief talk, which concluded the pro\ngram for the evening,\nj After the lectures many had become\nso interested in the exhibit that they\nspent a long while looking oW.c the\ncharts and various other things. This\nevening a large crowd is expected to\ncome out. Mr. Cosper manager of\nthe exhibit will make an address.\nW. B. NIMMONS\nPASSES AWAY\nPresident of Pine Bluff Concern Dies\nat His Home at Bluffton, Indiana,\nYesterday,\nW. B. Nimmons, president of the\nW. B. Nimmons Hardwood Mill in\nthis city, died late yesterday after\nnoon at his home in Bluffton, Ind., ac\ncording to a message received yester\nday evening by H. B. Bell, manager of\nthe local plant.\nMr. Nimmons has been sick for\nsome time. V. J. Rainey, vice presi\ndent of the company, has been attend\ning him for the past week. Mr. Bell\nwill leave this morning for Bluffton,\nInd., to attend the funeral, which\nwill most likely take place there. Mr.\nNimmons was quite well known here\nwhere he often visited in interest of\nthe stave factory and had many\nfriends.\nBIG DANCE AT FOREST PARK\nGiven by Barbers Union Local No.\n529, Pine Bluff, Ark., on June 20. Mu\nsic furnished by Pine Bluff Symphony\nOrchestra. Admission $1. Every\nbody invited. A good time assured.\n6-13-5t.\nSAFE\nBANKING\nIn every department is assured by\nthis bank, the oldest stote bank in\nArkansas, established in 1870.\nCareful management, courtesy, to\nj all, and a willingness to aid and ad\nvise means to every depositor \u201cSafe\n(Banking.\u2019\nOur Capital and Surplus\n$275,000.00\nNew accounts invited.\n\u2022M. P. Bank\nPine Bluff, Ark.\nViscount Maidstone and Margaretta\nDrexel at Races In England\nPhoto by American Press Association.\nThe marriage of Viscount Maidstone and Miss Margaretta Drexel is not\nonly to be a social affair in London, but it will bring a part of the Drexel\nmillions to the assistance of the young Englishman. Viscount Maidstone is\ndescribed as a typical Englishman, and his greatest hobbies are attending the\nraces and playing golf. This picture shows Viscount Maidstone and Miss\nDrexel at the races anxiously watching a horse backed by the Englishman.\nVISITOR TELLS\nOF LYNCHING BEE\nWilliam Hunter filtered Young: Girl\u2019s\nGoo in at Garnett and is Taken from\nOfficers and Lynched\u2014Was\nAn Orderly Affair.\nJohn Grumbles, of 8\u2018car City, was\nin the city yesterday and related the\nstory of the lynching of William Hun\nter, a negro, near his home town ast\nSaturday night. He said the lynch\ning was a quiet affair, there being no\ndisplay of rowdyism at any time during\nthe lynching. He was not present\nwhen the negro was lynched, nor does\nhe know any of the participants in\nthe lynching bee.\nMr. Grumbles says he learned that\nHun'.er entered the room of Miss\nRhoa Johnson, sister of State Sena\ntor Arthur J. Johnson, at Garnett,\nearly Saturday morning. The girl\nsaw him there and screamed. Hunter\njumped from a window, but was cap\ntured. Saturday afternoon he was\narraigned and held for the grand jury\nin default of a $2,000 bond. While\nhe was being taken to Star City, af\nter dark several officers were over\npowered and Hunter was taken from\nthem. Hunter was strung up on a\nlimb and several shots fired at the\nbody, the lynchers departing.\nMr. Grumbles says he learned that\nHunter had been employed at the\nj Johnson home for some years. His\nactions were rather strange of late\nj and he had been ordered to stay away\nI from the residence.\ni\ni Loans Wanted\u2014On bottom planta\nt on property. Long time, liberal\nterms, and moderate interest.\u2014Cot\nton Belt Savings Trust Co.\n6-15-4t.\nMrs. D. Lee has returned to her\nhome in Memphis, after a visit with\nDr. and Mrs. O. C. Hankison, in this\ncity.\nDrink Fan-Tas Its a winner 5c.\u2014\nDurham\u2019s. tf.\nSAM SPANN IS\n\u201cNOT GUILTY\u201d\nJudge Grace Instructs Jury to Return\nVerdict In Defendant's Favor Af\nter State Presents Its Side\nof the Case.\nIn the Jefferson circuit court yes\nterday afternoon, Judge A. B. Grace,\ngave peremptory instructions to a\njury to return a verdice of \u201cnot guil\nty\u2019\u2019 without leaving the jury box. Sam\nSpann, a well known negro farmer of\nthis county, was the defendant and\nhe was tried on a charge of being an\n'accessory after the fact to the killing\njby Leuvert Moore of Arch Nelson, a\n5 negro who was stabbed to death in\nSimmons store in the western part of\nthe city in November, 1908. Spann\nwas indicted by the Jefferson county\ngrand jury as an accessory to the\nmurder in that he was charged with\naiding Moore to make his escape af\n,ter the tragedy. It was claimed that\nSpann carried Moore out of the city in\nhis wagon and let him escape near\nTucker Plats.\nj Moore and Nelson had trouble over\n(Moore\u2019s wife, who was Nelson\u2019s sis\nter. Moore has never been heard of\n(or seen by a Pine Bluffian since the\nday of the killing.\nj About forty witnesess were sum\nmoned in the case yesterday. Judge\nW. D. Jones prosecuted Spann and the\ncourt appointed Judge E. J. Kerwin to\ni defend him. After the state exhausted\nj its testimony and rested, Judge Ker\nIwin submitted the case to the court\nand Judge Grace discharged all the\nwitnesses. He went over the case in\n(detail with the jury and gave per\nemptory instruction to return a ver\ndict of \u201cnot guilty.\u2019\u2019\nTARRY NEGRO IS\nCAPTURED HERE\nPatrolman Lem Reidinger made an\nI important arrest yesterday afternoon,\nj when he detained Jesse Cole, alias\nI Ward, a negro, about 20 years old,\nwho is wanted at Tarry, Ark., on a\nI\nIf you carry a watch. We have just received a\nfew watches that we propose to sell you at a bargain. i\nThink of it,\n17 JEWEL MOVEMENT IN 20 YEAR GOLD I\nFILLED CASE FOR $12.00.\nR. H. STEARNS CO.\nJewelers and Opticians\nI\ncharge ('1 breaking into the shop of\nHo!) Thomas, a few days ago. The\nnegro was at the corner of Fourth\navenue and Main st: et when arrested\nby Patrolman Reidinger al about 4\no clock. He was locki d up at head\nquarters and the authorities at Tarry\nwere notified of his arrest. Immediate\nly after his arrest he confessed that\nhe was the man wanted. The offi\ncers at Tarry state! that they would\ncome after the prisoner at once.\nREDEEMS AN OLD\nCOUNTY BOND\nCounty Treasurer Curriu M. Xichol,\nof this city, recently redeemed a Jef\nferson county five per cent funding\nbond, which was issued many years\nago and was reissued by County\nJudge \\V. D. .Tones in 1$D\">. The\nbond, for $T>00 was redeemed at par,\nCounty Treasurer Xichol thus saving\nthe county interest for five years. It\nwas clue August ID to. The bond\nwas presented for redemption by .1. (4.\nCahill a Xew York lawyer, who pre\nsented it for one of his clients. The\nredemption of the bond was necessary\nin order to wind up an estate in\nwhich it was involved.\nTELEPHONE LINE\nWAS DAMAGED\nW .II. Bellamy, of Altheimer, man\nager of the plant of the Altheimer\nTelephone Company, sepnt yesterday\nin the city on business. He reports\nthat the tornado of last Thursday\ndestroyed seven miles of a telephone\nline for his company.\nTORNADOES always come unan\nnounced and at a time when you least\nexpect them. Now is the time to let\nus write your tornado insurance. The\ncost is very low.\u2014Cotton Holt Savings\nTrust Co. 6-11-Gt.\nCoper Lowe of Monticellc, was in\nthe city yesterday visiting his broth\ners, Prof. A. W. Lowe, and Hr. W. T.\nLowe. Mr. Lowe left on the after\nnoon train for St. Louis, Washington\nand Annapolis. At the latter place\nhe will enter the naval school.\nPINE BLUFF BOY\nTO BE EMBALMER\nAdam Robinson, of Tills City, Among\nThose Examined by State Em\nbalming Board.\nL'ttle Rock, Ark., June 15.\u2014The\nState Embalming Board met in Little\nRock yesterday and examined 14 ap\nplicants for embalmers license. The\nBoard is composed of Harry Holder\nnoss of Pine Bluff, B. Grosse, Hot\nSprings; J. A. Pence, Conway; Dr. C.\nP. Runyan, and Dr. Joseph D. Shep\npard, president and secretary of the\nState Board of Health, Little Rock.\nThe applicants were: Alf H. Gruer,\nFort Smith; Ben Hammond, Morril\nton; B. M. Bowe, Fordyce; M. T. Bar\nger, Little Rock; J. T. Tidwell, Beebe;\nH. O. Giles, Kingsland; H. S. Speck,\nEl Dorado; Leroy Wood, Mena; Harry\nS. Riegel, Batesville; Adam Robinson,\nPine Bluff; B. W. Jackson, Little Rock\nJessie T. Jones, Fort Smith, and Rich\nard Waddell, Helena. The last three\nare negroes. The majority of the ap\nplicants have been students of an em\nbalming school conducted here for\nsome time at the College of Physi\ncians and Surgeons. After the writ\nten examination was completed late\nyesterday, the applicants were taKcn\nto the Hospital of Physicians and Sur\ngeons where they were put through a\nrigid examination in embalming, the\napplicants being required to make de\nmonstrations before the Board.\nA modern two story home for sale.\nLocated on W. 5th ave. convenient to\nbusiness section of city.\u2014Cotton Belt\nSavings Trust Co. 6-14-4t.\nSee the Piano tve are giving away\u2014\nKnstor A lilutlieutlial. 6-lG-13t'\nros UMBRELLA fixing\n1. Gllcksburg, the umbrella xuaa\nSecond and Walnut, opposite tela\nphone office. 7117.1\u2014\nEvery Man Needs One\nAn extra pair of pants. We have\na large assortment of Trouser Pat\nterns.\n^JTHE TAILOR\nYfest Second Up Stairs\nLiFt INSURANCE\nIN ARKANSAS\nReturn of Normal Financial\nConditions Indicated by\nLife Business.\nPINE BLUFF, $224,322\nUidoH of l\u00bb. ii. Duncan Received\n$.\u25a0>.>,000\u2014$582,30(1,(MM) Paid Out\nin United Stall's.\nJ^il\u2019i1 insurance organizations of the\nUnitod States and Canada distributed\n$\u2022>.{2,500,000 in 1909, according to\ncomputations by the Insurance Press.\nThe payments in tin two countries to\nbeneficiaries for death claims matured\nendowments, or other benefits under\nthe policies of level-premium compan\nies or the certificates of various life\ninsurance organizations\u2014assessment\nand the like\u2014amounted to $366,500,000\nThe estimated total of the amounts\npaid by regular companies in divi\ndends to policyholders for surrender\ned policies, to annuitants and on\nclaims in foreign countries was $166,\n000,000.\nSummation of life insurance pay\nments of all kinds in 1909:\nClaims paid in the United\nStates and Canada .$366,500,000\nPayments for dividends\nand for surrender values\nand to annuitants and\nforeign policy holders! es\ntimated) $166,000,000\nGrand total $532,500,000\nHark to Normal.\nTh<\u2018 regular life insurance business\nbegan its return to normal conditions\nlast year, the reports from all of the\nstates showing increase of payments\nfor deatii claims and endowments.\nThe reports of the fraternal societies\nshowed also increase of payments for\ndeath claims and benefits.\nEvidently the change of general\nconditions of trade and business\nfrom unfavorable to favorable, that\nis, the return of prosperity,\nhad effect in the life insurance\nfield sufficient to permit the carrying\nof insurance without considerable in\ncrease of liens through loans and also\nto reduce to a normal extent the lap\nsation of premium payments. With\na large amount of insurance taken by\nnew insurants and, in 'comparison\nwith the records for 1907 and 1908, a\ndecrease of ratio of Insurance drop\nped naturally the companies had to\npay more claims last year.\nLoans on Policies.\nAccording to the returns to the in\nsurance department of the State of\nNew York, where 90 per cent of the\ninsurance in force must be accounted\nfor, there was an apparent increase of\nabout $35,000,000 In loans on policies,\nas compared with increases of more\nthan $55,450,000 in 1908, $72,587,325 In\n1907, and $27.279326 in 1906.\nIn the past three years the appre\nciation of the value of life insurance\npolicies fer the protection, through\n(Continued on Page Four.)\nQuite sure you haven\u2019t forgotten\nanything? Have you a pair of our\nGrover Oxfords at $3.50? If not, you\nshould not delay getting a pair.\nGrover\u2019s Soft Shoes for tender feet\nare the most comfortable and most\ndurable ladies shoes made.\nLeverenz-Truloek\nShoe Co.\n226] Main","height":"29268","width":"19960"}}
